  <h1>The Method</h1>

  <p class="method-intro">Every analysis on this site runs through the same framework. It's built on published research in persuasion psychology, cognitive bias, and inoculation theory. This page explains what we detect, why it works on people, and where the science comes from.</p>

  <h2>Why This Exists</h2>

  <p>Social media is full of content designed to make you feel instead of think. Not all of it is wrong — some divisive posts contain true facts. But even true facts can be arranged to bypass your critical thinking through emotional escalation, tribal framing, and rhetorical sleight of hand.</p>

  <p>This site doesn't tell you what to believe. It shows you <em>how the content works on you</em> — the specific techniques, the specific language, the specific psychological buttons being pushed. Once you see the machinery, it's harder for it to operate on you without your awareness.</p>

  <p>That's not a metaphor. It's a research-backed intervention called <strong>inoculation theory</strong>.</p>

  <aside class="self-check">
    <span class="self-check-label">Self-check: what this page just did to you</span>
    <p>The three paragraphs above use <strong>emotional architecture</strong>. The opening hooks anxiety ("content designed to make you feel instead of think"). The middle escalates by naming specific threats ("emotional escalation, tribal framing, rhetorical sleight of hand"). The closing provides an empowerment exit ramp — "once you see the machinery" — that makes you feel protected for having read this far.</p>
    <p>"That's not a metaphor" is a <strong>thought-terminating pivot</strong>. It shuts down the instinct to treat the medical analogy as figurative and redirects you into accepting a clinical frame. It works the same way "let that sink in" works — it tells you to stop and accept rather than keep evaluating.</p>
    <p>We're not removing these. The anxiety is real — manipulative content does bypass critical thinking. The empowerment is real — inoculation does build resistance. But you should see the persuasive scaffolding holding up even a truthful message.</p>
  </aside>

  <h2>Inoculation Theory — The Foundation</h2>

  <p>In the 1960s, psychologist William McGuire demonstrated that people could be made resistant to persuasion the same way they're made resistant to disease: by exposure to a weakened form of the attack. Show someone <em>how</em> a manipulative argument works — before they encounter it in the wild — and they develop cognitive antibodies against it.</p>

  <p>Recent work has confirmed this holds for misinformation specifically. van der Linden and colleagues showed that explaining manipulation techniques in advance reduced susceptibility to misinformation about climate change. Roozenbeek and van der Linden demonstrated the same effect through a browser game that taught players to create fake news — players who understood the production techniques became better at recognizing them.</p>

  <p>Every analysis on this site is a dose of that weakened form. You read the original post, you see the technique identified, and you understand the psychology behind it. Next time you scroll past something similar, the pattern is already flagged in your head.</p>

  <h3>The Research</h3>

  <ul class="reference-list">
    <li>McGuire, W.J. (1964). "Inducing Resistance to Persuasion: Some Contemporary Approaches." <em>Advances in Experimental Social Psychology</em>, 1, 191–229. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0065-2601(08)60052-0">doi:10.1016/S0065-2601(08)60052-0</a></li>
    <li>van der Linden, S., Leiserowitz, A., Rosenthal, S., & Maibach, E. (2017). "Inoculating the Public against Misinformation about Climate Change." <em>Global Challenges</em>, 1(2). <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/gch2.201600008">free full text</a></li>
    <li>Roozenbeek, J. & van der Linden, S. (2019). "Fake News Game Confers Psychological Resistance Against Online Misinformation." <em>Palgrave Communications</em>, 5(65). <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41599-019-0279-9">free full text</a></li>
  </ul>

  <aside class="self-check">
    <span class="self-check-label">Self-check: the citation blanket</span>
    <p>This page cites a lot of research. That density is an <strong>appeal to authority</strong>. Stacking named researchers, journal titles, and DOI links creates a weight of credibility that can make the framework feel unquestionable — the same mechanic we flag when a Facebook post says "Harvard researchers found..." to shut down scrutiny.</p>
    <p>The difference we're claiming: every citation above links to the actual paper. You can read McGuire's original 1964 work, check whether we're representing van der Linden's findings accurately, and decide for yourself whether the research supports what we say it supports. The citations exist so you can verify us, not so you'll defer to us.</p>
    <p>But notice how that distinction — "our citations are checkable, theirs aren't" — is itself a persuasive move. It positions us as the trustworthy ones. Whether we've earned that trust is something you should decide after checking, not before.</p>
  </aside>

